     WebTV style

     abbreviation: Make sure it¿s in common use. For instance, the word
     celeb¿ is puzzling to some viewers. Use celebrity¿ or star¿
     instead.

     and more: This is definitely a case where (and) more is less. It
     sounds as if we don¿t know what else to say. Let¿s avoid it.

     capital letters: For improved readability, avoid using all-capital
     letters for emphasis. Boldface important text instead.

     check out this...: sample of hackneyed, pushy writing that is
     unlikely to create interest among our viewers. Please avoid using
     °check outý as well as the cliche °cool site.ý

     client: The software installed in the WebTV Internet Terminal. Not
     the viewer or the customer.

     Club WebTV members: Not Club WebTV Members. Note that it is Club
     WebTV, not ClubWebTV.

     commas: Follow AP guidelines on serial commas.

     contractions: Try to avoid contractions to increase scannability.

     email: No hyphen. Note that it is not Email unless the word begins
     a sentence.

     exclamation points: Use them sparingly. Choose your words
     carefully and let the words themselves exclaim.

     etc.: Please avoid it.

     Explore¿s categories: Explore Entertainment, not Entertainment
     Home Page; Explore Kids, not Kids Home Page...

     FAQs: Frequently asked questions. Like AM, PM, LA, DC and many
     other commonly used acronyms, names and abbreviations, it takes no
     periods.

     home page: Two lower-case words. When referring to WebTV (version
     2.1): Web Home and TV Home.

     Internet, Net: "Net" is short for Internet (which is always
     capitalized), so "Net" should also be capitalized. Don¿t
     capitalize netizen.

     information: Not info.

     italics: Avoid them wherever possible. They are less readable than
     plain or bold text in the WebTV user interface.

     message watch: Not messagewatch

     Net: Short for Internet; therefore capitalized. But use

     newsgroup: Not Newsgroup.

     numbers: spell out whole numbers below 10, use numerals for 10 and
     above.

     ok: Not °okayý

     online: No hyphen.

     paragraphs: No indents on paragraphs. But one return between each
     paragraph.

     periods: One space between periods and next word, not two. For a
     cleaner look, avoid periods (points) wherever possible: US, USA,
     AM, PM.

     quotation marks: For a cleaner look within the limited space of
     the WebTV matrix, avoid quotation marks wherever possible.

     To set off the titles of plays, songs, books, TV shows, use upper
     case as if in AP headline style: Does Your Chewing Gum Lose Its
     Flavor on the Bedpost Overnight? Gone With the Wind, The Brady
     Bunch, All¿s Well That Ends Well.

     Use quotation marks when quoting somebody or to set off a
     nickname. Within headlines, if quotation marks are necessary, use
     single quotes, not double.

     Caution: Don¿t let a good quote slip by in the interest of
     avoiding quotation marks. Good quotes enliven content.

     select: Not click.

     Spotlight: A well-researched Explore article incorporating related
     pages embedded as links in the text.

     Tidbit: The working name for clever packaging for aggregated
     Explore content.

     URL: An acronym for Uniform Resource Locator, it should be written
     in all caps. For our viewers, although, the preferred term is Web
     address.

     viewers: Our customers are °viewers.ý They are not surfers,
     subscribers or users.

     Web, World Wide Web, Web site: Web site is two words. The W in Web
     and World Wide Web are always capitalized.

     Web address: Term we use to direct our viewers to a Web page or
     Web site. See also URL.

