     Rules for Teases and Link Language

     Rule: Link language must be clear.
     Writing copy for WebTV is unique because the process of
     downloading pages places extra demands on viewers¿ time. Having
     invested that time, viewers are extremely unforgiving when obscure
     language leads them to unpredictable destinations.

     When writing for WebTV, then, clarity of language and
     predictability of result are essential. Obscure or overly "cutesy"
     copy discourages viewers from following links. When viewers follow
     misleading links, they feel betrayed--as if they¿d been caught in
     a °bait and switchý scam--and are less likely to follow other
     links. In fact, they may not come back at all. Our viewers simply
     don't like guessing games.

     Rule: Every tile must contain at least one descriptive element
     that cues the user to the link¿s purpose.
     Successful "link languageý gives viewers a clear sense of what to
     expect. Every tile should contain at least one element (title,
     logo, subhead or html text) that clearly communicates where the
     viewer will be taken. This needn't be verbose. A few words
     separated by commas can communicate the site's purpose ("puns,
     puzzles, trivial pursuits"). In other cases, a logo ("TV Guide")
     can sufficiently cue the viewer.

     Rule: Links must live up to their promises.
     A link on the Explore Main page might pose a question, °What's the
     most livable city in the US?" If the link takes viewers to Explore
     Money, with no indication where to go to find the promised
     information, they¿ll be left feeling frustrated and confused.
     Instead, the link should lead the viewer directly to the page that
     contains the promised information.

     Rule: The promised destination should be visible at all times to
     avoid user error. Never link to a rotating stack.
     When a destination is hidden behind a rotating stack, unless
     viewers are focusing on the stack at the precise moment the
     corresponding tile appears, they have no idea where to go.

     Rule: When promoting an Explore category, use a general tease, not
     a specific Web site. The predominant graphic should reference the
     category. For example, "Today in Explore Money.ý
     Sometimes, teases are designed to take the user to a general
     Explore category, as opposed to a specific site within that
     category. When that is the goal, the tease should make that intent
     clear. For example, a tease for the Entertainment category might
     read °What¿s hot in Entertainment!ý across the top in a large-size
     font, followed by a graphic or some html text from sites within
     the category. The strong verbal and visual reference cues viewers
     that they will be taken to the general category rather than to a
     specific site.

     Rule: We are in the information-delivery business. Wherever
     possible, we should take the viewer directly to the information
     promised.
     Avoid teases that link to teases that link to teases. In one
     example, a tease in the home page linked to a tile in a category
     front page, which in turn linked to a Spotlight that linked to
     other sites. The viewer had to navigate a maze to find the
     promised information.

     Rule: Writing must pass the clarity test. Before submitting your
     copy, ask yourself:
     1. Does the tease clearly describe where the link will lead?
     2. Does this link lead directly to the destination promised?
     3. Is there any way the text might be misconstrued?

