     Legal guidelines for graphics

     Graphics includes logos, photographs, and illustrations. The
     possible sources include a website, hard copy (to be scanned), and
     a stock photo or graphics service.

     Graphics can be downloaded and used from a website ONLY if the
     website belongs to an Explore Partner. For more information about
     how partner graphics can be used, refer to
     http://webhost-1/partner/legal.htm. If a graphic from a
     non-partner site is desired, we need written permission in order
     to use the graphic, even if we are using that graphic to link to
     their site. Hard copy falls under the same distinction as graphics
     from a website. We can scan graphics only with permission,
     preferably from materials provided by the website.

     Any use of graphics from a website or related hard copy must link
     directly to the website. The graphics cannot be used as
     illustrations for other purposes, nor can they promote other areas
     of the service. There cannot be any intermediate links; e.g.,
     linking from the home page to Explore to the website. The graphic
     from the website must be a link to the website; it cannot merely
     be an illustration in an article that links to the website.

     The use of stock photos varies according to the stock photo
     source. There are two important distinctions to be aware of when
     using stock photos (or stock illustrations, or clip art): whether
     or not the photos are royalty-free, and whether the use of the
     photos is editorial or promotional. The question of whether we are
     editorial or promotional is still unsettled.

     [Use of stock photos within Explore is editorial provided the link
     goes directly to the website that is illustrated by the stock
     photo. If the photo is used to promote WebTV's own pages, then it
     is promotional content. For instance, if a photo on the Explore
     main page uses a stock photo of the Taj Mahal, and that photo
     links to a site about the Taj Mahal, that is editorial usage. If
     the main page photo links to Explore Travel, and within Explore
     Travel there is an article about the Taj Mahal, then it is
     promotional use, because the photo was used to promote Explore
     Travel, not the Taj Mahal site.]

     **OR**

     Use of stock photos within Explore is editorial.

     The distinction between editorial and promotional usage is
     important both for reasons of pricing and credit. If usage is
     editorial, then it is not necessary to have a release for any
     people depicted in the photos. However, it is necessary to credit
     the photographer and/or the stock photo agency. With promotional
     use, it is not necessary to credit the photographer or the agency.
     However, it is necessary to obtain releases for any models or
     celebrities depicted in the photos.

     The distinction can be thought of like this: If Michael Jordan's
     photo is in the Chicago Tribune, the Tribune does not pay Jordan
     for the use of his likeness. However, they do credit AP or UPI or
     whoever took the photo. On the other hand, if Michael Jordan has
     his likeness on a box of Wheaties, he is paid for the use of his
     imageÙbut the photographer does not get a credit on the box of
     cereal.

     The method for crediting photographers and agencies is still
     unsettled. Currently we are putting the credit on the image, which
     is what is commonly done in print and on the web. Because of
     NTSC's low resolution, this credit is illegible. The other option
     is to include a list of credits under the Setup menu. This would
     need to be updated for each new photo (possibly daily). Some
     photographers or agencies may consider this "burying" the credit
     and find it an unacceptable solution.

     The problem of credits and releases can be avoided entirely by
     using royalty-free photos only. However, celebrity photos can only
     be obtained through a release, or through a PR news service
     available through Presslink. Each agency at Presslink has
     different regulations; read the license and pricing information
     for each agency before purchase.

     Legal guidelines for site logos:

     The site logos are treated differently than other graphics. In
     this case, the producer submits a request to partnerships that
     they want to use a site's logo in the subcategory level of Explore
     (this assumes that they have already checked the Content database
     and confirmed that we don't have an agreement with this site
     already). Partnerships verifies that listing this site in Explore
     will not jeopardize partnership or ad sales negotiations. If it
     does, Partnerships alerts the producer that it is inadvisable to
     list the site at this time. If there is no conflict, then
     Partnerships sends a letter to the site requesting permission to
     use the logo or other identifying graphics from the site (and also
     requesting a photoshop or eps version of the graphic). The letter
     is worded in such a way that a lack of reply on the site's part is
     de facto permission for us to use the logo.

     If there is no reply after seven working days, or if permission is
     granted, Partnerships alerts the producer that it is OK to list
     that site with its logo. The producer then alerts Design to create
     the site icon. If permission is denied, the producer can either
     display the site with a generic icon, or choose not to display the
     site.

     If the site logo is displayed and then notice is received that
     permission to use the logo is denied, or a cease and desist order
     is received, then the logo (and if necessary, the link itself) is
     removed from the system.

