     Style and Consistency In Tidbits and 20% Tiles

     Tidbits are concise, but there¿s still plenty of room for
     cleverness. Every tidbit should be brief but powerful. Each link
     should tell viewers exactly where they¿re going to go. Be clever
     but be clear; be descriptive rather than vague or obscure.

     Every tidbit should end with a period, a question mark, or a
     close-quote mark.

     Discuss

     Is Dr. Kevorkian a criminal?
     Mercy-killing at talk.euthanasia.

     Writer.com
     Where writers and wannabe writers can talk.

     Beware of rhetorical questions or judgmental statements. We lead,
     but we don¿t editorialize.

     avoid: First they cloned sheep, then monkeys. who¿s next?

     That¿s a Fact

     Only seven women have ever been on the FBI¿s 10 Most Wanted list.

     Six out of 10 whites approve of interracial marriage--Gallup Poll

     That¿s a Fact should be written in simple, declarative sentences.
     Cite the source if there¿s room.

     Hear Here
     Hear Here should be written in simple, declarative sentences. Make
     sure the audio site works before you link to a page. WebTV
     supports wave, au, aiff, mpeg2 layer 3 and real audio. We do not
     support liquid audio.

     Energy-fused techno and hard-hitting beats for your dancing feet
     at needledrop.com

     Says Who?
     The hardest thing in the world to understand is the income
     tax.¿--Albert Einstein

     Always put quote marks around the quote. The period at the end of
     the sentence goes inside the quote mark. Put a long dash
     (option-shift-dash) before the name of the person who said the
     pithy remark. Put a space before and after the long dash. Links
     from the quote should be intuitive; for instance, this one could
     link to the IRS.

     Did You Know?

     You can investigate a mutual fund online.

     These should be statements that tell viewers about interesting and
     useful things they can do online.

     Game Time

     Trust no one until you've played the X-files X-test.

     Game Time should be written as a one-line teaser leading viewers
     to an online game. It can be a question or statement that clearly
     explains what the game is and what they should expect.

