     Spotlights

     Spotlights are a cornerstone of the WebTV experience. There are as
     many different kinds of spotlights as there are kinds of
     programming categories.

     By pointing the viewer to a well-chosen series of links,
     Spotlights educate. They entertain. They are mission-oriented --
     they provide answers to a question, they solve a problem, they
     entice viewers to explore further.

     Spotlights are *not* written because there¿s a space that needs
     filling. Spotlights are *not* simply a list of Web sites.
     Spotlights are *not* exercises in flashy writing style and deep
     thought.

     Spotlights have the same reasons for being as a news story or
     feature or column. Each Spotlight gives us a chance to share our
     expertise in picking great Web sites and our enthusiasm for the
     Web. Each Spotlight brings the viewer into contact with valuable
     nuggets of knowledge, insight, wisdom or wit, or, if we¿re lucky,
     all of the above.

     Each Spotlight, in short, tells viewers something they didn¿t know
     before. Each Spotlight is in itself a terrific WebTV experience
     that makes the viewer want more.

     Linking from Spotlights:
     1. Link destination should be clear (for instance, °restaurantsý
     instead of °places to nosh¿¿).
     2. A link shouldn¿t wrap from one line to the next, because then
     it will look like two links. Check to see how your links display.

     Spotlight Examples

     No. 1
     Have you ever wondered what it would be like to take a boat ride
     down the Seine? Well, this just may be the time to take a trip to
     Paris! The Eiffel Tower. The Champs Elysees. The cafes. Ah, the
     City of Light!

     One of the main attractions in Paris is the Louvre. This beautiful
     museum was built centuries ago. It houses thousands of works of
     art by some of the world's most famous artists. Check out the Mona
     Lisa, or the Venus de Milo.

     The Parisian architecture is sure to delight. The boulevards and
     cafes are famous the world over. The beautiful and elegant
     restaurants are sure to be enjoyed by any and all.

     It is said that the bread in France is, well, the best thing since
     sliced bread! Have a baguette and see for yourself!

     Some people say that the Parisians can't STAND Americans. We don't
     know if there's real truth to this stereotype, but it might help
     to take a few French lessons before embarking on your trip. As
     quick as you can say, "bonjour!" you'll be conversing with the
     natives!

     What makes this a weak Spotlight?

     Let's look at this sentence by sentence:

     "Have you ever wondered what it would be like to take a boat ride
     down the Seine?"
     There's a good chance the reader might say: "Well, no, actually I
     haven't. I think I'll stop reading this right now and find
     something a little more exciting to read, like Mike's Freaky Home
     Page." Question lead-ins are fine in some instances, but it's
     tempting to use them too often.

     Well, this just may be the time to take a trip to Paris!
     "Oh really? Can I go? Goody, goody, goody. (Don't tell the reader
     when might or might not be a good time for him/her to take a
     trip.)

     The Eiffel Tower. The Champs Elysees. The cafes. Ah, the City of
     Light!
     Cliche landmarks, followed by another cliche. With such mundane
     observations, even an exclamation point won¿t entice viewers to
     click.

     One of the main attractions in Paris is the Louvre.
     Even if some viewers don't know what the Louvre is, a sentence
     like this isn't going to interest them in it.

     This beautiful museum was built centuries ago.
     Beautiful? How so? What does it look like? And how many centuries
     ago? Two? Two hundred? Vagueness will drive viewers away in
     droves.

     It houses thousands of works of art by some of the world's most
     famous artists.
     How many thousands? Three thousand? 999,000? What "works of art"?
     What famous artists? Again, too vague.

     The Parisian architecture is sure to delight.
     Are you guaranteeing this? And just who is it supposed to delight?
     (And why? You're not even telling me what it looks like.)

     The boulevards and cafes are famous the world over.
     If they¿re so famous, why do we have to tell the reader they are?
     "Famous" is a boring description. Say why they're famous.

     The beautiful and elegant restaurants are sure to be enjoyed by
     any and all.
     No more guarantees, please. And that passive voice makes sentences
     needlessly wordy and hard to read.

     It is said that the bread in France is--well, the best thing since
     sliced bread!
     Passive voice (it is said), corn, a clichÕ and an aren't-I-clever
     exclamation point at the end.

     Have a baguette and see for yourself!
     That exclamation point again. And linking from baguette¿ won¿t
     tell viewers what experience they¿re in for.

     Some people say that the Parisians can't STAND Americans.
     Avoid capital letters. Here, it feels juvenile.

     We don't know if there's real truth to this stereotype, but it
     might help to take a few French lessons before embarking on your
     trip.
     If we don¿t know, let¿s not say it

     As quick as you can say "bonjour!" you'll be conversing with the
     natives!
     Gee! Is that another WebTV guarantee? Who knew conversing in
     French was so easy? Besides, the correct word is °quickly.ý

     No. 2
     Just in time for the summer tourist season, Air France has done
